sourceQuestion:
Consider the following scheme for implementing a critical section in a situation with three processes P_1, P_2, and P_3:

repeat
  flag[i] := true;
  while flag[j] or flag[k] do
  begin
    if turn == j then
      flag[i] := false;
    while turn != i do skip;
    flag[i] := true;
  end;
  critical section
  flag[i] := false;
until false

(The program is for process P_i; P_j and P_k are the other two processes. turn is initially set to some process.)

a) Does the scheme ensure mutual exclusion in the critical section? Briefly explain.

A. Yes, mutual exclusion is guaranteed because each process checks flag[j] and flag[k] before entering
B. No, mutual exclusion can be violated when two processes simultaneously pass their respective flag checks
C. Yes, the turn variable ensures only one process enters at a time
D. No, the flag mechanism with three processes creates race conditions

